climbs.name: 1-900-LUV-KUSH
climbs.fa: FA Kendra Mazur, Kushwant Bussawah, Steve Chua, Cat Chow, Eric Tran July 2022

content.description:
WARNING: This is a newly developed climb. There may still be some grit and loose rock. Wear a helmet and do not loiter around the base.

NOTE: KUSH is an extremely potent strain of local cannabis. It is a favorite of the FAists.

Extremely well bolted easy lead. Ends on the ledge 3/4 up the wall.



Between Great Yellow Hope and Brown and Veiny at the upper Conroy's Castle ledge.

8 bolts, chain anchors.

climbs.name: A Child’s Christmas in Wales
climbs.fa: Matthew Howells, Cody Stock, Erik Frebold 2015

content.description:
This is a newer, well-featured route that should be beginner friendly. Enjoy a fairly tall single-pitch on slab and jugs, and take in the views at the top.

Far left of Conroy's, at the base of a ramp that moves up to a ledge on the right.
8 bolts

WARNING: This is a newly developed climb. There may still be some grit and loose rock. Wear a helmet and do not loiter around the base.

Start up the slab, gets steeper at the top.

The belayer should keep a tight belay to prevent a ledge fall on the last 2 bolts. The last bolt is placed so that when you do the last move your waist is at the bolt if you use a short draw or single carabiner.



Second bolt line to the right of Small is Beautiful on the upper left tier of Conroy's Castle.

Bolts

WARNING: This is a newly developed climb. There may still be some grit and loose rock. Wear a helmet and do not loiter around the base.

Start up the the horizontal ledges and scoops and up the slab. Gets steeper near the top.

The climb is well bolted but the belayer should keep the rope tight on the last few bolts as there is a bit of a ledge.



First bolt line to the right of Small is Beautiful on the upper left tier of Conroy's Castle.

Bolts.

climbs.name: Asian's Gumby Superhighway
climbs.fa: E Tran, Kushwant Bussawah, Steven Chua, March 2021

content.description:
WARNING: This is a newly developed climb. There may still be some grit and loose rock. Wear a helmet and do not loiter around the base.

Shares the same first move as Emil and the Detectives. Follow the right bolt line.

Do it in 2 pitches, if done in one pitch bring slings to reduce drag.

2 raps with a 60m rope gets you down.



Right by Emil and the Detectives.


P1 - 6 bolts, P2 - 9 bolts.

If linking the pitches bring 16 draws and slings.

This route shares a start with Instant Classic, but heads straight up instead of trending right. The bolts are a little sparse and the first is a little high.

Between Kingfisher and IC (shared start)
5 bolts

climbs.name: Brown & Veiny
climbs.fa: Kushwant Bussawah, Kendra Mazur, Eric Tran, Steven Chua

content.description:
Start right of I Love You 3000. Follow the line of bolts. Crux is the slab exit. Hand jam the final moves. 



Obvious start right of ILY 3000


12 bolts and bolted anchor. Bolts are spaced close together so you can get away with skipping a few. Rap off the left or right

Fun and technical climbing up high quality rock make this a worthwhile climb when in the area. Although it's not a long climb, you might notice a good pump when clipping the final bolt and pulling onto the slab below the anchors. 
  
 I think the name is a reference to the derelict car in the forest that appears to have been used for target practice.

This is the first climb considered to be on Conroy's Castle rather than the Forgotten Wall, although the two walls are contiguous.  This climb is where the wall starts to curve to the south.
6 bolts and bolted anchors

A popular climb, but not only because it's one of the easier climbs in the area.  The first pitch (5.9) is a little less than vertical and requires careful sequence planning making it an enjoyable puzzle.  The second pitch (5.7) is a lower angle affair with great holds.

Conroy's Castle is really the southern end of the Forgotten Wall, so walking south along the base of the Forgotten Wall, you've arrived at Conroy's Castle when the climbing ceases to look like 5.11 or 5.12, and the cliff is curving around to face south.  Charlotte's Web is left of the climb Clear Cut which is distinguished by having a fun-looking roof about 10m up.
8 or 9 quickdraws if doing it in two pitches, about 15 to link the pitches (which I would recommend). Bolted first and second pitch anchors.  From the top of the second pitch double ropes would be required to rappel all the way to the ground, so use the first belay station as an intermediate rappel if on one rope.

Good face climbing with a fun little roof about a third of the way up.

6 bolts, with a bolted anchor
Right of Charlotte's Web there's a flat area at the base of Clear Cut.  The little roof helps identify the route.

A great two pitch addition to Conroy's Castle; a bit like Charolette's Web without the tricky sequences and more continuity on the 2 pitches.  The first pitch is nice 5.8 face climbing, and the second was also good-- perhaps a touch harder.

Left of Charolette's Web, an obvious wear streak.
Bolts.  Easily led in 1 pitch with ~10 draws.

Consistent. Slightly exhilarating, but youll have protection where you need it. There is a low first bolt for belayer safety on the ledge.

5 bolts

climbs.name: The Great Yellow Hope
climbs.fa: Steven Chua, Eric Tran, Kushwant Bussawah

content.description:
***Newly developed - loose dirt and rock still on route. Wear a helmet.

Well-featured slab and ledge-like footholds for the first three quarters or so, about 5.7 or a light 5.8 in difficulty. The crux is at the top with one or two 5.9 moves with trickier footwork that eventually work their way into nice handholds.



Just to the left of Brown and Veiny. To the right of Asian Princess. Keep to the right of the bolt line, following the ledges and well-featured slab.


10 bolts. Rap rings at the top. Self-funded.

Follow the bolt line straight up to a ledge. The crux is at the 6th bolt. Remember to look right if going straight up seems hard. Bring an extendable draw for the last bolt, past the crux. Good feet!

Lower off anchors at the top. 



Start on the ramp left of Kingfishers Catch Fire, clip the first bolt then move straight up.

7 bolts, rap rings at the top (2)

Fun slab climb. Foot holds are a little thin around the second bolt, but definitely worth climbing!

6 bolts to anchors.

Recently fully bolted. Start out on relatively easy slab, trending slightly left over a few ledges. More jugs up top.

Just right of a patch of vegetation and left of the joint start for Bangers/Instant
9 bolts

Climbs up a steep stemming corner to the base of a tricky ramp with a fun move up onto the face above for a few more moves to finish. There are not many easy climbs in this area, a good warm up and easy lead.

About 50 feet to the right of Bullet the Blue Car, just past two projects. Pretty much the last route on Conroy's Castle before you walk into the Forgotten Wall area.
6 bolts, bolted anchor.

A easy romp up incuts and bulges on the far left side of Conroy's Castle.  Begin from a vegetated ledge.

bolts.

This area is home to some of the only less-than-vertical rock in Chek and one of the few multi-pitch routes.  It's also the only area in Check, other than the Foundation Wall to offer 5.8 and 5.9 sport climbs, and they're quite good too.
